  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Eulogy on the Painting of Two Ministers in Retirement, with Preface
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The nine blessings of the Hong Fan speak of five fortunes: first is longevity, second is wealth, third is peace and health, fourth is love of virtue, and fifth is a natural death. Mencius said, "There are three supreme honors in the world: rank, age, and virtue." Thus Qizi, the sage of the Shang, when visited by King Wu of Zhou, expounded the eternal principles—placing longevity first, wealth second, and virtue third—to show the common truth of all under heaven, his words being elaborate and expansive. As for peace and natural death, these naturally fall within longevity. Yet when Mencius came to the state of Qi, he spoke of the three supreme honors to awaken the ruler, placing rank first, age second, and virtue third, his words necessarily brief and constrained by circumstance. Both these sages were worthy men of their age, and though their teachings differ in sequence and detail, both stressed virtue, rank, and age—the three things honored alike in ancient and modern times. Thus a scholar who achieves one of these three while missing the other two, or gains two while lacking the third, need not be reckoned behind the sages and gentlemen. How much more then when all three are complete without lack?

    Now the Choi brothers of Changwon, both renowned for their literary talents, rose to the highest rank. Their loyal service to the state and love for the people shine forth in history as models of their generation. When they retired in succession to their native place, not a day passed without their enjoying each other's company—truly embodying the five complete fortunes and all three supreme honors. Such a man appears once in a thousand years, yet here two brothers flourish together in a single age! We have commissioned the painter Park Jayun to paint The Two Ministers in Retirement, a glory to the court, so that the father and son of Nanling of the Han cannot claim sole beauty.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hong Fan (洪範): A section of the Book of History detailing the Five Blessings fundamental to Chinese moral philosophy.'
    - 'Qizi (箕子): The sage of the Shang dynasty who transmitted the principles to King Wu of Zhou after the dynasty''s fall.'
    - 'The three supreme honors (達尊): Virtue, rank, and age—the universal marks of distinction recognized across ages.'
    - 'Nanling father and son: A reference to the celebrated father-son duo Liang Ji and Liang Shang of the Han dynasty, known for their virtue and influence.'
